00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:30.140
So here's what we saw. We didn't see any dose-limiting toxicity.

251
00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:34.510
We didn't see any grade two CRS cytopenias with what

252
00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:36.820
we were expecting, and there were no deaths on study.

253
00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:40.820
Now, we used the same product for these patients in first remission as we did for

254
00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:44.640
the relapse patients. And what we saw was a huge difference in the

255
00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:48.320
degree of toxicity generally and in particular,

256
00:14:48.640 --> 00:14:52.620
neurological toxicity, which was at 80%, and in this setting was down

257
00:14:52.700 --> 00:14:56.460
to 17%. So what we were hoping to be the case, at least in that

258
00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:56.840
setting,

259
00:14:57.820 --> 00:15:01.580
was realized. So we were relieved, to say the

260
00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:05.600
least, about that. Did the cells expand in this setting?

261
00:15:05.660 --> 00:15:09.450
The expansion looked pretty much the same as we'd seen in the relapse patient over

262
00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:15.060
here. Again, this is in the first

263
00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:19.000
month. Persistence was out here to about

264
00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:22.800
four to five months with this one outlier,

265
00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:25.680
and it correlates to the fact that we saw B-cell recovery.

266
00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:29.810
When the CAR T-cells go down to a certain level, you see B-cell recovery, and

267
00:15:29.840 --> 00:15:33.320
that's what we were seeing here. So it's not long-term surveillance that we're

268
00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:35.500
inducing here, at least by this approach.

269
00:15:35.580 --> 00:15:38.410
There's other things we're doing that are designed to extend that.

270
00:15:38.420 --> 00:15:42.300
At least in this series, this is what it looks like in the first three months

271
00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:46.220
after treatment. They do traffic to the

272
00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:50.230
CNS because we did LPs in these people after therapy, whether they

273
00:15:50.230 --> 00:15:53.810
did or not have disease. We didn't inject chemotherapy, but we tested to see

274
00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:57.820
whether you could find these cells in the CSF, and a percentage of the

275
00:15:57.840 --> 00:16:00.080
T-cells that were there were CAR.

276
00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:04.580
So it is trafficking there, and I'll come back to that point in just a minute.

277
00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:09.200
Because we were trying to preserve people's conditions so they weren't, if you

278
00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:12.800
will, brutalized or handicapped by the therapies that we were doing,

279
00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:17.300
we did cognitive performance, walking speeds, frailty scores, all those sort of

280
00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:21.330
adjunct things that we do in oncology right now to try to assess what happens

281
00:16:21.340 --> 00:16:25.000
to a person when you do something to them that's anti-cancer.

282
00:16:25.009 --> 00:16:28.780
And what we saw was that their performance actually improved because we were seeing

283
00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:32.680
them really after induction therapy, and so they regained pretty much back

284
00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:36.660
to baseline after this. So we didn't think we were doing anybody

285
00:16:36.680 --> 00:16:38.900
any harm. And the question is, did we do anybody

286
00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:42.840
any good? And this is what it looks like so far.

287
00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:47.460
So this is the first 18 patients. This is the overall survival. Everybody's alive.

288
00:16:48.040 --> 00:16:50.960
And there were two patients who had a molecular relapse.

289
00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:54.830
One was PH positive, one was not. They were retreated,

290
00:16:55.020 --> 00:16:56.380
and they were taken to transplant.

291
00:16:56.440 --> 00:16:59.700
So these two tick marks are on this curve.

292
00:16:59.760 --> 00:17:00.360
So they're still

293
00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:02.020
alive

294
00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:04.540
and in remission.

295
00:17:05.980 --> 00:17:09.681
So for this phase of the talk, we could see that we could actually

296
00:17:10.161 --> 00:17:12.641
administer to older patients. It was safe.

297
00:17:13.340 --> 00:17:17.280
They did well. They expanded even in a low antigen setting because we

298
00:17:17.320 --> 00:17:19.440
weren't really sure whether that would happen.

299
00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:23.440
The T-cells do get to the CSF, and we've not seen a CNS relapse so far.

300
00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:26.080
And so we're doing a confirmatory

301
00:17:27.820 --> 00:17:31.420
study supported by Autolus, who have really been our good

302
00:17:31.480 --> 00:17:32.660
partners for a while

303
00:17:33.640 --> 00:17:36.870
in exploring these. And it's going to be a multicenter trial at Memorial, City of

304
00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:39.660
Hope, and Stanford for a larger number of people, 40,

305
00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:44.540
30 of whom will have PH negative disease and 10 of whom will have PH positive

306
00:17:44.580 --> 00:17:48.460
disease, and see if these early observations can be seen in a large

307
00:17:48.540 --> 00:17:50.420
number of patients at different institutions.

308
00:17:50.810 --> 00:17:54.760
And more importantly, can you really do something and finish

309
00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:57.240
the therapy in the first three months from diagnosis?

310
00:17:57.340 --> 00:18:00.660
That would be just wonderful if we could pull that off.

311
00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:04.420
So we will see, and it'll be a field effort to make that happen.

312
00:18:05.820 --> 00:18:09.520
But the other part of this talk that I'll finish with has to do with addressing CD

313
00:18:09.600 --> 00:18:13.330
negative ALL relapse because everybody's getting blinatumomab as part of

314
00:18:13.360 --> 00:18:17.150
the frontline therapy. When they relapse, I think it's

315
00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:19.420
about 30% of the patients will have CD19

316
00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:24.420
negative. And when you relapse post

317
00:18:24.800 --> 00:18:27.220
blinatumomab, you can see that the survival,

318
00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:31.876
either after blin or after CAR T-cells, is notGreat in

319
00:18:31.936 --> 00:18:35.836
people who are adults. And with CD19, what we've

320
00:18:35.896 --> 00:18:39.516
seen is that about 25%, 30% of the patients have relapsed, have

321
00:18:39.616 --> 00:18:43.316
lost CD19, either from a selective pressure on a pre-existing

322
00:18:43.396 --> 00:18:47.016
clone, which I think is probably the more common one than a

323
00:18:47.096 --> 00:18:49.855
genetic mutation or alternative splicing.

324
00:18:49.896 --> 00:18:52.956
They are mechanisms that work, but the point is that the

325
00:18:53.796 --> 00:18:57.736
ScFv on the CAR won't recognize this, and therefore won't

326
00:18:57.796 --> 00:19:00.406
target that leukemia cell. So the question is, what else could we do?

327
00:19:01.576 --> 00:19:05.506
We've been working on another target, BAFF-R, on the context of

328
00:19:05.516 --> 00:19:08.946
lymphoma. BAFF-R is a B-cell activating factor.

329
00:19:08.946 --> 00:19:12.316
It's a member of the TNF superfamily, and it's pretty much expressed

330
00:19:12.416 --> 00:19:15.476
on most B cells, from the early B cell all the way

331
00:19:15.556 --> 00:19:19.436
to CLL. We were interested in it

332
00:19:19.476 --> 00:19:23.236
because we thought, based on some B-cell biology, that it was

333
00:19:23.436 --> 00:19:27.236
less likely to be deleted as a resistance mechanism since it

334
00:19:27.316 --> 00:19:31.136
appeared to be an essential component of B-cell survival, which is the

335
00:19:31.176 --> 00:19:34.856
reason why we were focused on it. So Larry Kwok

336
00:19:35.736 --> 00:19:39.516
had generated a monoclonal antibody against the natively folded BAFF-R.

337
00:19:40.636 --> 00:19:43.816
Our lab with Shuli Wang worked with his in developing a

338
00:19:43.856 --> 00:19:47.336
second-generation BAFF-R CAR that was humanized, had a CD4

339
00:19:47.376 --> 00:19:50.936
transmembrane domain, and a 4-1BB intracellular

340
00:19:50.996 --> 00:19:52.236
signaling domain.

341
00:19:54.916 --> 00:19:56.676
You've seen this slide a million times.

342
00:19:56.756 --> 00:20:00.456
We all show the same sort of approach to apheresis,

343
00:20:00.546 --> 00:20:03.796
transduction, and at a dose escalation of cells because this had not been

344
00:20:03.836 --> 00:20:07.456
done before. It was another first-in-human trial

345
00:20:08.356 --> 00:20:11.156
with standard lymphodepletion and then a CAR T cell infusion.

346
00:20:11.206 --> 00:20:12.456
And the question is, what happened?

347
00:20:14.216 --> 00:20:15.236
The cells expand.

348
00:20:16.316 --> 00:20:20.296
This shows you just by copy number, and I think, yeah, this is by copy number, and

349
00:20:20.336 --> 00:20:21.256
this is detecting

350
00:20:22.356 --> 00:20:26.236
cells by flow. And they are very typical, at least in our hands, to what we

351
00:20:26.296 --> 00:20:30.196
saw with CD19. It's about three to four months of detectability

352
00:20:30.236 --> 00:20:33.836
by the methods we use, which is really molecular and by flow.

353
00:20:33.936 --> 00:20:36.596
So you can't tell what target this is by this.

354
00:20:36.636 --> 00:20:37.376
It looks kind of

355
00:20:38.416 --> 00:20:38.936
the same.

356
00:20:39.996 --> 00:20:41.575
There were no dose-limiting toxicities.

357
00:20:41.635 --> 00:20:45.436
You can see in the bottom that toxicity was really well tolerated.

358
00:20:45.516 --> 00:20:49.096
Some grade 1 and very little CNS toxicity.

359
00:20:49.136 --> 00:20:51.096
And these are patients with active lymphoma.

360
00:20:53.676 --> 00:20:56.896
And these are the results so far, the green being people who are

361
00:20:56.916 --> 00:21:00.546
continuing in remission. And the trial hopefully will

362
00:21:00.836 --> 00:21:02.296
continue to accrue over the next

363
00:21:03.216 --> 00:21:07.026
year to really see what it can do in the various forms of lymphoma, which is

364
00:21:07.076 --> 00:21:11.056
mantle cell and transformed lymphoma and large cell lymphoma of

365
00:21:11.116 --> 00:21:11.796
B-cell type.

366
00:21:12.696 --> 00:21:12.976
But this

367
00:21:13.916 --> 00:21:16.936
section's about ALL. So the question is, what about ALL?

368
00:21:17.056 --> 00:21:19.186
So I went to Larry, and I talked to him.

369
00:21:19.186 --> 00:21:23.126
I said, "We ought to look and see whether this is expressed on pre-B ALL,"

370
00:21:23.196 --> 00:21:25.226
because if you looked in the literature, it wasn't obvious that it was.

371
00:21:25.256 --> 00:21:28.976
So we looked at 92 samples from 71 patients and found that it

372
00:21:29.056 --> 00:21:31.856
was expressed in about 80% of the

373
00:21:31.896 --> 00:21:34.556
patients. It is lower

374
00:21:35.716 --> 00:21:39.576
than in mature B-cell neoplasms, so that was a concern.

375
00:21:40.736 --> 00:21:44.636
And we saw that at least in the patients who had lost their CD19 because of

376
00:21:44.676 --> 00:21:48.036
CD19 CAR or BLIN, they still expressed

377
00:21:48.456 --> 00:21:50.876
BAFF-R in about two-thirds of the patients.

378
00:21:50.976 --> 00:21:54.436
So it supported at least exploring whether the CAR we use for

379
00:21:54.476 --> 00:21:57.096
lymphoma could be used to treat patients with

380
00:21:57.976 --> 00:22:00.696
ALL in that setting. So we said, "Well, let's

381
00:22:01.556 --> 00:22:05.216
do another first-in-human trial for patients with relapsed

382
00:22:05.496 --> 00:22:09.436
ALL who had failed a CD19 CAR." That was the

383
00:22:09.456 --> 00:22:12.396
patient population. We actually did preclinical studies.

384
00:22:12.456 --> 00:22:16.436
Shuli Wang did this in her lab, which is right next to mine,

385
00:22:16.516 --> 00:22:20.436
so I was seeing this evolve. And you can see in the

386
00:22:20.476 --> 00:22:23.696
bottom that the BAFF-R CAR would

387
00:22:24.616 --> 00:22:28.296
kill not only CD19-expressing leukemia

388
00:22:28.316 --> 00:22:29.046
cells, but it would

389
00:22:31.696 --> 00:22:35.676
target cells that had lost CD19. And

390
00:22:35.776 --> 00:22:39.736
so we knew that we had a potential salvage for people who had lost CD19

391
00:22:39.816 --> 00:22:43.766
due to prior therapy with a CD19-specific antibody, this

392
00:22:43.856 --> 00:22:46.596
bispecific or a CAR T cells. So,

393
00:22:47.555 --> 00:22:51.416
as you can see there, the BAFF-R CAR, unlike the CD19 CAR,

394
00:22:51.425 --> 00:22:55.216
demonstrated anti-tumor activity against CD19-negative patient-derived

395
00:22:55.256 --> 00:22:56.696
xenografts. And so that told us

396
00:22:57.516 --> 00:22:59.796
it looks the same, it behaved the same.

397
00:23:00.056 --> 00:23:01.716
What will it do in somebody who has

398
00:23:03.036 --> 00:23:06.476
this disease? So we did this trial, which was led by Ibrahim

399
00:23:06.516 --> 00:23:07.036
Aldos.

400
00:23:08.376 --> 00:23:11.856
The City of Hope was at our other ALL trials. Same thing.

401
00:23:11.916 --> 00:23:15.816
They failed or were ineligible for a CD19-targeted therapy,

402
00:23:16.576 --> 00:23:19.596
and we accepted anybody who had BAFF-R expression.

403
00:23:19.636 --> 00:23:23.436
And this concerned us because the antigen density or the

404
00:23:23.456 --> 00:23:27.016
receptor density, I should say, on this cell is not what

405
00:23:27.056 --> 00:23:30.276
CD19 is on a B cell. So we weren't exactly sure, the mice

406
00:23:30.456 --> 00:23:34.076
notwithstanding, whether it would be seen by the

407
00:23:34.136 --> 00:23:34.536
CAR.

408
00:23:36.476 --> 00:23:39.516
And so that was one of the obvious questions that we had.

409
00:23:40.476 --> 00:23:44.396
So these were the patients, and you can see dose level one, dose

410
00:23:44.436 --> 00:23:48.326
level two. We were very much guided or restricted by the FDA, what

411
00:23:48.336 --> 00:23:50.456
we could do, as fast as we could do it.

412
00:23:51.916 --> 00:23:55.696
This was cyclophosphamide alone, followed by

413
00:23:55.956 --> 00:23:59.576
the dose level one, and then we added traditional fludarabine

414
00:23:59.616 --> 00:24:01.236
cyclophosphamide at the same dose.

415
00:24:01.256 --> 00:24:04.636
This is a pretty low dose of CAR T

416
00:24:04.676 --> 00:24:08.146
cells. And what we saw was that there was expansion,

417
00:24:08.676 --> 00:24:11.986
just like they saw in lymphoma, in the patients with relapsed ALL.

418
00:24:13.116 --> 00:24:15.796
This is copy number and percent by flow.

419
00:24:17.396 --> 00:24:19.656
And this is what we've seen so far in the patients

420
00:24:20.636 --> 00:24:24.296
who, in this most recent dose level, who got

421
00:24:24.456 --> 00:24:28.296
the BAFF-R CAR with flu psi

422
00:24:28.856 --> 00:24:31.346
and 50 million cells, they've all gone into

423
00:24:31.456 --> 00:24:34.664
aA remission

424
00:24:35.704 --> 00:24:37.904
in molecular with no detectable disease by

425
00:24:38.784 --> 00:24:42.004
ClonoSEQ. So we believe there's a signal there

426
00:24:42.884 --> 00:24:46.864
that there may be an alternative to people who have a CD19 relapse or who do

427
00:24:46.944 --> 00:24:50.314
not express CD19. We've all been looking for this.

428
00:24:50.344 --> 00:24:53.464
CD22 has been there. It's not

429
00:24:53.984 --> 00:24:56.604
evolved the way I think people had hoped, and so I

430
00:24:57.544 --> 00:25:00.584
treat all of this with considerable caution, even in our own group.

431
00:25:00.664 --> 00:25:04.304
But we want to pursue this and see just where it will take us.

432
00:25:05.184 --> 00:25:08.304
So it demonstrated favorable safety profile and

433
00:25:08.664 --> 00:25:12.324
flirtatious, I would say, clinical activity in patients who had

434
00:25:12.604 --> 00:25:15.084
progressed after a CD19-directed therapy.

435
00:25:15.784 --> 00:25:19.524
There was expansion, and now we're going to complete an expansion phase and then

436
00:25:19.564 --> 00:25:21.304
hopefully work on to a

437
00:25:22.604 --> 00:25:26.504
larger number of patients. We have made, as Michel was

438
00:25:26.544 --> 00:25:28.594
implying in his introductory remarks, a

439
00:25:28.924 --> 00:25:32.124
bispecific CAR that expresses both

440
00:25:32.584 --> 00:25:33.584
Baff-CAR,

441
00:25:34.864 --> 00:25:38.464
scFv, and a CD19, because what we really want to do is

442
00:25:38.544 --> 00:25:42.404
test that for patients with relapsed ALL to see if we

443
00:25:42.444 --> 00:25:45.024
can get more people into remission deeper and

444
00:25:46.204 --> 00:25:47.124
more durable.

445
00:25:48.104 --> 00:25:48.384
So,

446
00:25:49.344 --> 00:25:53.024
thank you for your attention. I'm grateful to Autolus for

447
00:25:53.164 --> 00:25:57.024
partnering with us and going further, to the Leukemia Society,

448
00:25:57.104 --> 00:26:00.084
who was the first person who looked at this and said, "We want to fund that,"

449
00:26:00.364 --> 00:26:01.644
before the NCI did,

450
00:26:02.924 --> 00:26:06.844
and of course, to the staff with whom I work with and the

451
00:26:06.984 --> 00:26:09.224
field that's making this happen. So thank you very much.

452
00:26:14.764 --> 00:26:18.264
So I'm happy to take questions. If you do, if you please go to the microphone

453
00:26:18.284 --> 00:26:21.864
because there are people listening at home, who would like to be able to hear it

454
00:26:22.144 --> 00:26:22.544
also.

455
00:26:29.984 --> 00:26:30.124
Okay.

456
00:26:30.344 --> 00:26:31.704
Steve, maybe I'll start with one.

457
00:26:33.604 --> 00:26:37.124
It's about quantifying the level of

458
00:26:37.184 --> 00:26:38.204
expression of either-

459
00:26:38.264 --> 00:26:38.654
Of the Baff-CAR?

460
00:26:38.654 --> 00:26:39.464
... CD19 or Baff.

461
00:26:41.304 --> 00:26:45.204
Do you think that all these CD19 negative relapses are truly

