... 78% of patient express, right?

492
00:28:16.494 --> 00:28:16.724
Mm-hmm.

493
00:28:17.124 --> 00:28:20.764
So how about the dynamic range? Like how many percentage of

494
00:28:21.524 --> 00:28:23.704
cells express that target?

495
00:28:24.244 --> 00:28:28.184
So what I was told by Abraham, who did this with the pathologist, he said he

496
00:28:28.224 --> 00:28:32.144
was worried that the expression was low, certainly not

497
00:28:32.264 --> 00:28:36.104
as what we see in other targets. And so there's even a variation

498
00:28:36.124 --> 00:28:39.744
within the low. But we were taking, if we can detect it,

499
00:28:40.084 --> 00:28:42.584
if we can see it at all, we allow people onto the study.

500
00:28:45.064 --> 00:28:48.064
So another question, if the cell expression

501
00:28:49.124 --> 00:28:52.354
has some kind of correlation with target expression?

502
00:28:52.804 --> 00:28:53.184
With what?

503
00:28:53.544 --> 00:28:54.794
With target expression.

504
00:28:55.124 --> 00:28:56.104
I don't think so.

505
00:28:56.824 --> 00:29:00.804
It's not a lot of patients yet, of course,

506
00:29:01.344 --> 00:29:04.434
but I don't think we could see that those with the highest level of low

507
00:29:04.504 --> 00:29:07.944
expression expanded better than the lowest level of low

508
00:29:08.004 --> 00:29:10.884
expression. I think for the moment it's unknown.

509
00:29:11.324 --> 00:29:12.084
Okay. Thank you.

510
00:29:12.304 --> 00:29:12.724
Thank you.

511
00:29:17.064 --> 00:29:20.804
We'll take all three questions. I hope they're short questions or two questions.

512
00:29:21.684 --> 00:29:25.084
My questions are kind of off the wall, but I'm just going to run them by you

513
00:29:25.144 --> 00:29:28.944
anyway. Do you ever see epitope spread of any sort with CAR

514
00:29:28.984 --> 00:29:30.294
T-cell therapy?

515
00:29:31.234 --> 00:29:31.234
Mm.

516
00:29:31.264 --> 00:29:34.934
And the other one is, do any of these B-cell directed

517
00:29:35.744 --> 00:29:39.244
therapies have a potential role in other

518
00:29:39.324 --> 00:29:42.744
non-malignant B-cell driven diseases like some of the really vicious

519
00:29:43.304 --> 00:29:47.024
autoimmune diseases for which rituximab and such

520
00:29:47.644 --> 00:29:48.544
antibodies are used?

521
00:29:49.184 --> 00:29:50.704
So the second question is easy to answer.

522
00:29:50.744 --> 00:29:54.184
The rheumatologists are really all agog about

523
00:29:54.224 --> 00:29:57.464
utilizing these cellular-based therapies, in part because of

524
00:29:58.044 --> 00:30:01.104
work that shows that you get a different type of depletion

525
00:30:02.404 --> 00:30:05.764
with a cell than you do with antibodies. So we have done that.

526
00:30:05.864 --> 00:30:07.744
We are seeing that, and trials are opening for that.

527
00:30:07.804 --> 00:30:10.674
It's a big deal in the field, and the patients are knocking at the

528
00:30:10.744 --> 00:30:14.664
door. With regard to the first question on antigen spread, I think what

529
00:30:14.704 --> 00:30:18.284
we have seen, it's hard to see it in heme malignancy, but in solid tumors

530
00:30:18.944 --> 00:30:19.684
for sure,

531
00:30:20.524 --> 00:30:23.424
we have seen responses, certainly in our models,

532
00:30:24.644 --> 00:30:28.394
and in some patients where we got a complete response.

533
00:30:29.044 --> 00:30:32.564
But we knew that the tumor didn't express antigen across the board.

534
00:30:32.704 --> 00:30:35.884
And so we think that's the engagement of an endogenous response, whether it's

535
00:30:35.904 --> 00:30:39.844
epitope spreading or just liberating an endogenous anti-tumor response is what

536
00:30:39.904 --> 00:30:43.464
I think is going on, and we want to focus on that because we think there are T-cell

537
00:30:43.484 --> 00:30:46.884
receptors in that population that should be harnessed and

538
00:30:46.964 --> 00:30:50.824
utilized as a partner to a CAR T-cell in a solid tumor.

539
00:30:50.904 --> 00:30:52.034
That's the direction we're going in.

540
00:30:55.374 --> 00:30:59.174
You showed this remarkable difference of cytokine release syndrome and

541
00:30:59.234 --> 00:31:02.154
ICANS in patients that got the CARs in remission-

542
00:31:02.274 --> 00:31:02.394
Yeah

543
00:31:02.454 --> 00:31:04.764
... versus at relapse.

544
00:31:05.134 --> 00:31:05.334
Yes.

545
00:31:05.974 --> 00:31:06.114
So

546
00:31:07.014 --> 00:31:09.913
you showed also 100% response rate and overall survival.

547
00:31:10.694 --> 00:31:14.474
I think is this a matter of tumor load or what do you

548
00:31:14.534 --> 00:31:15.434
explain this for?

549
00:31:18.294 --> 00:31:22.234
So I think so. I think when

550
00:31:22.294 --> 00:31:25.934
we see people who are getting these cells with advanced disease, whether it's

551
00:31:25.974 --> 00:31:28.714
myeloma or lymphoma, leukemia, it's

552
00:31:29.654 --> 00:31:33.534
a real adventure in that first month. So we were worried about that.

553
00:31:33.714 --> 00:31:36.734
We were worried about two things, too much toxicity or not enough activity.

554
00:31:36.794 --> 00:31:40.714
And I think what we have so far is it's not that toxic and there's a hint

555
00:31:40.774 --> 00:31:42.044
of activity, and

556
00:31:43.054 --> 00:31:44.634
for us right now, it's about durability.

557
00:31:45.114 --> 00:31:47.814
Are we going to see relapses at two years, and what will they look like?

558
00:31:47.934 --> 00:31:48.954
So time will tell us.

559
00:31:50.694 --> 00:31:51.054
Thank you.

560
00:31:51.994 --> 00:31:52.974
One last question from

561
00:31:53.994 --> 00:31:54.114
the

562
00:31:55.014 --> 00:31:58.034
online. Is your trial still open? Just a quick answer.

563
00:31:59.174 --> 00:32:01.294
The BAF-AR clinical trial.

564
00:32:02.134 --> 00:32:02.654
So we are

565
00:32:03.914 --> 00:32:07.444
working to keep it open. It has to do with some relationship with the company and

566
00:32:07.474 --> 00:32:07.914
everything,

567
00:32:09.354 --> 00:32:12.734
for whom we made the virus. But we're going to make our own version of that and

568
00:32:12.774 --> 00:32:16.014
keep going the BAF-AR, because there's a big need for that, for sure.

569
00:32:17.854 --> 00:32:19.254
Okay. Thank you very much.

570
00:32:22.574 --> 00:32:25.714
It gives me great pleasure to introduce our next speaker, Dr.

571
00:32:25.954 --> 00:32:28.104
Phil Greenberg, who's professor

572
00:32:29.094 --> 00:32:32.914
of medicine and professor of immunology at the Fred Hutchinson

573
00:32:33.014 --> 00:32:36.834
Cancer Research Center in Seattle. He needs no introduction.

574
00:32:37.154 --> 00:32:38.194
Phil, thank you for being here.

575
00:32:38.634 --> 00:32:40.114
And I didn't get one, so that works.

576
00:32:41.134 --> 00:32:45.034
Okay, so I'm going to try to go quickly through a lot of

577
00:32:45.044 --> 00:32:48.744
material here about how we're trying to manipulate and

578
00:32:48.774 --> 00:32:52.494
engineer an immune system so that it can work against tumors

579
00:32:52.894 --> 00:32:56.604
in a solid tumor environment. So these are my disclosures.

580
00:32:57.154 --> 00:32:59.824
None of them are really going to be terribly relevant to what I'm going to talk

581
00:32:59.874 --> 00:33:03.683
about. So what's needed for a successful immunotherapy

582
00:33:03.874 --> 00:33:05.174
targeting a solid tumor? Well,

583
00:33:06.154 --> 00:33:08.204
you have to have a good tumor target antigen.

584
00:33:08.274 --> 00:33:11.454
That's largely become a computation problem with the ability

585
00:33:11.554 --> 00:33:15.354
to essentially sequence everything and find out

586
00:33:15.374 --> 00:33:19.194
exactly what's uniquely or differentially expressed.

587
00:33:19.214 --> 00:33:21.994
You need a receptor on the T cell that's efficient.

588
00:33:22.474 --> 00:33:26.364
And again, that's now become a technical and/or synthetic engineering problem.

589
00:33:26.874 --> 00:33:30.303
I'll show you some of the synthetic engineering that we're doing.

590
00:33:31.294 --> 00:33:35.134
You need T cells able to infiltrate and recognize the tumor cells.

591
00:33:35.194 --> 00:33:39.034
Again, that's partly cell processing, making cells that actually

592
00:33:39.054 --> 00:33:40.243
can survive and home better.

593
00:33:41.134 --> 00:33:44.634
But also, again, you can do some of this with synthetic

594
00:33:44.694 --> 00:33:48.034
engineering. And finally, they have to persist in sustained

595
00:33:48.074 --> 00:33:51.484
function. Once again, how you process the cells and

596
00:33:51.654 --> 00:33:55.334
what kind of synthetic molecules you put in can have an

597
00:33:55.374 --> 00:33:56.634
enormous impact on that.

598
00:33:58.234 --> 00:34:02.214
So our studies in solid tumors really started when Ingunn Stromnes was a

599
00:34:02.234 --> 00:34:04.874
postdoc in my lab. She now has her own lab in Minnesota.

600
00:34:05.934 --> 00:34:09.814
And these studies have gone on now for quite a few years, quite a

601
00:34:09.854 --> 00:34:13.274
few postdoc lives. Most of them have survived, actually.

602
00:34:13.334 --> 00:34:16.594
And it was a collaboration with Sunil Angerani originally.

603
00:34:17.234 --> 00:34:20.834
So this was the original paper we showed in this

604
00:34:20.894 --> 00:34:24.294
engineered mouse KPC model. They spontaneously develop

605
00:34:24.694 --> 00:34:27.294
pancreatic cancer that replicates the human disease.

606
00:34:28.415 --> 00:34:32.124
And what Ingunn showed is that we could engineer T cells

607
00:34:32.234 --> 00:34:36.174
expressing a mesothelium-specific TCR, now, not a CAR, TCR,

608
00:34:36.814 --> 00:34:40.694
that they'd infiltrate, they would not only kill tumor cells,

609
00:34:40.754 --> 00:34:44.554
but they cause stromal involution, so this dense fibroblastic reaction

610
00:34:44.955 --> 00:34:48.034
disappeared. Unfortunately, though, they became dysfunctional.

611
00:34:48.114 --> 00:34:51.955
And in order to get therapeutic advantage in those mice, we needed to do

612
00:34:51.995 --> 00:34:55.874
repeated infusions. So we needed to do something to increase survival, and

613
00:34:55.915 --> 00:34:59.634
I'll get to how we do that now. But we also showed that we

614
00:34:59.694 --> 00:35:03.164
could generate human T cells also with a high affinity mesothelium

615
00:35:03.214 --> 00:35:07.014
receptor, and that that would kill at least human pancreatic

616
00:35:07.034 --> 00:35:10.734
cells in vitro. And so based on that, we initiated a clinical

617
00:35:10.854 --> 00:35:11.294
trial,

618
00:35:12.894 --> 00:35:16.754
with the expectation that we would be able to readily reproduce what we had seen in

619
00:35:16.794 --> 00:35:20.614
the KPC model. And this was with Gabby and Ode directing it, and

620
00:35:20.674 --> 00:35:23.754
Yapeng Xu, a postdoc in my lab, doing the analysis.

621
00:35:23.874 --> 00:35:27.284
And what we saw was we gave T cells, and we would wait

622
00:35:27.854 --> 00:35:30.694
21 days to analyze the toxicity.

623
00:35:31.854 --> 00:35:35.494
If they were doing well, they would qualify for a second infusion and potentially

624
00:35:35.534 --> 00:35:39.134
for a third infusion, always at least 21 to 28 days

625
00:35:39.194 --> 00:35:42.374
later. We got tumor biopsies pre-therapy,

626
00:35:42.874 --> 00:35:46.534
post-therapy, as well as a large number of blood samples to

627
00:35:46.614 --> 00:35:50.134
analyze. So we treated nine patients on this trial.

628
00:35:50.914 --> 00:35:53.934
Six of them got categorized ultimately as stable disease.

629
00:35:53.994 --> 00:35:57.904
We clearly saw evidence of tumor shrinkage, but

630
00:35:57.934 --> 00:36:01.154
none that would actually meet the resist criteria for being a formal

631
00:36:01.214 --> 00:36:05.154
partial response. And all of these patients

632
00:36:05.214 --> 00:36:09.114
eventually progressed. So to say the least, this was disappointing

633
00:36:09.134 --> 00:36:12.794
and not what we were hoping for, although we saw that there was some evidence of

634
00:36:12.834 --> 00:36:16.194
activity. But we thought maybe by analyzing

635
00:36:16.254 --> 00:36:20.174
the outcome of this in more detail, we would get some insights in how

636
00:36:20.194 --> 00:36:23.794
to make this better in patients. So this is looking at T

637
00:36:23.894 --> 00:36:27.654
cells in the blood that have the TCR we put in.

638
00:36:27.694 --> 00:36:31.554
We can barcode them. You can see we get a huge diversity of T

639
00:36:31.634 --> 00:36:34.744
cells. This is over the whole course of time that we were

640
00:36:34.794 --> 00:36:35.774
sampling.

641
00:36:36.594 --> 00:36:40.434
But if you look at day seven, day 14, day 21, what we

642
00:36:40.454 --> 00:36:41.434
see is mostly

643
00:36:42.254 --> 00:36:44.534
stem-like memory T cells in the blood.

644
00:36:45.394 --> 00:36:48.554
They start transitioning at day 21, but

645
00:36:48.614 --> 00:36:52.278
these were functional T cells.Which

646
00:36:52.298 --> 00:36:55.898
surprised us in terms of that we weren't seeing then a better response.

647
00:36:55.958 --> 00:36:59.078
So we then looked at what we were getting out of the tumor biopsies.

648
00:36:59.138 --> 00:37:00.968
This is, again, looking at

649
00:37:01.798 --> 00:37:05.378
all the cells in the tumor biopsy. You can see the tumor and the T cell

650
00:37:05.458 --> 00:37:06.258
clusters there.

651
00:37:07.198 --> 00:37:07.478
But if

652
00:37:08.318 --> 00:37:11.778
we then focus in on particular cells so that we only look at cells that

653
00:37:11.818 --> 00:37:15.718
express the TCR, they're obviously seen in the T cell group, and the

654
00:37:15.738 --> 00:37:19.118
mesothelin is expressed quite abundantly in the tumor group.

655
00:37:19.438 --> 00:37:23.338
But if we now compare the molecular signature of these T cells in the tumor

656
00:37:23.878 --> 00:37:27.778
to the molecular signature we were getting from single-cell RNA sequencing

657
00:37:27.818 --> 00:37:31.618
in the blood, you can see that they hardly overlap. They're really quite distinct.

658
00:37:31.698 --> 00:37:34.858
So what we're seeing in the tumor is very different than what we're seeing in the

659
00:37:34.938 --> 00:37:38.818
blood. And predictably, what it was, was a lot of functional

660
00:37:38.898 --> 00:37:40.318
signals. They weren't proliferating.

661
00:37:40.668 --> 00:37:44.598
They expressed DIGIT, CD39, TIM3, PD1, all of the

662
00:37:45.018 --> 00:37:48.638
inhibitory molecules. So we then looked at this in a little bit more

663
00:37:48.678 --> 00:37:52.358
detail. This is now just looking at CD8 T cells in a tumor,

664
00:37:52.778 --> 00:37:56.758
and I'm circling this cluster, which was a highly dysfunctional

665
00:37:56.798 --> 00:37:59.618
population when we studied each cluster for function.

666
00:38:00.738 --> 00:38:04.678
Perhaps not so surprisingly, those are all the T cells that expressed the TCR

667
00:38:04.718 --> 00:38:07.418
that we had expressed in the T cells we gave.

668
00:38:07.778 --> 00:38:11.118
They were quite distinct from the endogenous cells, which were the rest of the

669
00:38:11.158 --> 00:38:15.098
cells, but most of these were bystander cells that were just pulled in by

670
00:38:15.138 --> 00:38:17.878
the inflammation. So if you ask, do they function?

671
00:38:17.938 --> 00:38:21.198
Well, those bystander cells are producing interferon if you stimulate them.

672
00:38:21.598 --> 00:38:25.318
But these cells that we gave were no longer producing

673
00:38:26.598 --> 00:38:30.138
interferon at day 21. They expressed TIM3 and all the other

674
00:38:30.158 --> 00:38:32.978
markers. They expressed an exhaustion pathway.

675
00:38:33.658 --> 00:38:37.358
But one of the things that was really distinctive was their exhaustion pathway

676
00:38:37.858 --> 00:38:41.208
was not as severe as you see in classical canonical

677
00:38:41.278 --> 00:38:44.878
exhaustion. They had exhaustion genes, but not to the same

678
00:38:44.938 --> 00:38:48.418
extent. But what they did have is a very dominant TGF-beta

679
00:38:48.518 --> 00:38:51.878
pathway signature, suggesting that they were seeing TGF-beta.

680
00:38:53.438 --> 00:38:56.958
So we went back and looked now. We had done several different TCR trials,

681
00:38:57.758 --> 00:38:58.978
and other people have looked at T

682
00:38:59.918 --> 00:39:03.358
cells out of patients that were treated with infusions.

683
00:39:03.378 --> 00:39:07.078
And we looked in melanoma, pancreatic cancer, breast

684
00:39:07.118 --> 00:39:10.218
cancer, lung cancer, healthy blood, endogenous cells.

685
00:39:10.248 --> 00:39:14.208
And I think what I just want to highlight here is how distinctive this was, that

686
00:39:14.218 --> 00:39:18.007
the cells that we gave have an exhaustion signature, but

687
00:39:18.058 --> 00:39:21.838
it's really different from what's, for example, reported in melanoma or in

688
00:39:21.898 --> 00:39:25.758
mouse models in LCMV. It's a really mitigated signal

689
00:39:25.838 --> 00:39:29.778
compared to the score you get in cells that become classically exhausted.

690
00:39:30.538 --> 00:39:33.898
What they do have, though, is a very dominant TGF-beta signature.

691
00:39:34.268 --> 00:39:38.258
And once again, that's not typically seen, for example, in TILs that come out

692
00:39:38.298 --> 00:39:41.758
of melanoma, where there's a very minimal, if any, TGF-beta

693
00:39:41.858 --> 00:39:45.558
signature. So that was a really unique aspect of this

694
00:39:46.918 --> 00:39:50.868
issue, this disease. And the other thing is, which I think is probably

695
00:39:50.938 --> 00:39:54.898
not surprising, is blood is not representative of what's happening in a tumor.

696
00:39:55.018 --> 00:39:56.787
So the simple idea,

697
00:39:57.718 --> 00:40:00.498
straightforward idea, that you would just get cells out of the blood and you could

698
00:40:00.578 --> 00:40:01.758
monitor what was happening,

699
00:40:02.558 --> 00:40:04.858
seemed pretty unclear, at least in this solid tumor.

700
00:40:06.538 --> 00:40:10.378
So in order to actually start fixing this, we needed an analyzable model

701
00:40:11.198 --> 00:40:15.038
to resolve those obstacles. And fortunately, that's what the KPC

702
00:40:15.158 --> 00:40:18.798
mouse model of genetically engineered pancreatic cancer is so good for.

703
00:40:18.828 --> 00:40:21.298
And without... I'm not going to show you the data.

704
00:40:21.358 --> 00:40:24.918
This is a paper that's being submitted to Cell in the next week,

705
00:40:25.078 --> 00:40:28.758
actually. But what we know is that the

706
00:40:28.798 --> 00:40:32.358
KPC mouse replicated everything we saw in terms of this

707
00:40:32.398 --> 00:40:34.318
molecular signature we saw in humans.

708
00:40:34.658 --> 00:40:38.078
It was distinctive in terms of mitigated exhaustion and a

709
00:40:38.398 --> 00:40:41.818
TGF-beta signal. So I'm not going to show you the blood analysis

710
00:40:41.878 --> 00:40:44.838
and the single-cell analysis. I'm going to show you just the...

711
00:40:44.878 --> 00:40:47.258
This is now looking at spatial transcriptomics.

712
00:40:47.298 --> 00:40:51.138
This is an H&amp;E stain or tumor biopsy from a patient from a mouse

713
00:40:51.178 --> 00:40:54.958
treated. You get the same cell clusters if you do

714
00:40:55.698 --> 00:40:57.358
spatial analysis using the

715
00:40:58.638 --> 00:41:02.178
Visium and Xenium platforms. Mesothelin is

716
00:41:02.238 --> 00:41:04.738
expressed in the area where the tumor is.

717
00:41:05.218 --> 00:41:08.658
T cells are kind of found throughout the pancreatic

718
00:41:09.917 --> 00:41:13.658
biopsy. But what's seen is there's kind of clusters of

719
00:41:13.718 --> 00:41:17.598
cells. Some are in the tumor cell core, and there's others that

720
00:41:17.638 --> 00:41:19.658
are in this cluster, which is largely

721
00:41:20.458 --> 00:41:22.198
a tertiary lymphoid structure.

722
00:41:23.118 --> 00:41:26.998
A whole variety of T cells. I'm going to focus on three classic types, the

723
00:41:27.038 --> 00:41:30.938
TPECs, the T effector cells, and then this unique T

724
00:41:30.958 --> 00:41:34.718
effector exhausted TGF-beta cell that we found in

725
00:41:34.738 --> 00:41:37.758
humans also. And what you can see is the effectors and

726
00:41:37.778 --> 00:41:41.678
the TPECs are all found in these lymphoid

727
00:41:41.738 --> 00:41:45.518
aggregates that are near APCs, not in the

728
00:41:45.538 --> 00:41:49.438
tumor core. And if you look where the cells that have this

729
00:41:49.498 --> 00:41:52.978
exhausted TGF-beta signature, they're all embedded in

730
00:41:53.058 --> 00:41:56.118
the tumor cluster itself. They've infiltrated.

731
00:41:56.498 --> 00:42:00.198
They're in the cluster, but as you know, you already saw, they're not functional

732
00:42:00.238 --> 00:42:04.228
anymore. And again, you can do this nearest neighbor analysis, and you can

733
00:42:04.298 --> 00:42:07.618
see that the cells that have this exhausted signature are

734
00:42:07.798 --> 00:42:11.438
all surrounded by tumor cells, and the cells that

735
00:42:11.938 --> 00:42:15.678
have the functional phenotype are near endothelial cells, which is

736
00:42:15.718 --> 00:42:19.518
classically where these TLS niches

737
00:42:19.578 --> 00:42:20.798
form. So

738
00:42:22.018 --> 00:42:25.518
there's a very unique signature here of highly dysfunctional cells.

739
00:42:25.998 --> 00:42:29.898
It's associated with both persistent exposure to antigen, that's why they're

740
00:42:29.918 --> 00:42:33.258
in the tumor core, and exposure to TGF-beta.

741
00:42:33.978 --> 00:42:37.558
Now, the simple solution we thought was we could always knock out the TGF-beta

742
00:42:37.618 --> 00:42:41.528
receptor, and particularly since it has a mitigated exhausted signature,

743
00:42:41.578 --> 00:42:44.158
that ought to work well. Well, it didn't work at all, really.

744
00:42:44.558 --> 00:42:48.358
What it did do is it got rid of the TGF-beta signature, but very

745
00:42:48.618 --> 00:42:51.498
rapidly, these cells all acquire a

746
00:42:51.618 --> 00:42:55.578
full-fledged exhaustion signature, now looking like the

747
00:42:55.638 --> 00:42:59.158
classical T cell exhaustion signature you see in LCMV

748
00:42:59.218 --> 00:43:02.682
or in melanoma.So that's not a solution.

749
00:43:02.742 --> 00:43:04.782
So again, I'm skipping a lot of data.

750
00:43:04.822 --> 00:43:06.822
This will obviously all be in the paper.

751
00:43:07.402 --> 00:43:11.242
What we then did was a CRISPR screen, after doing a computational

752
00:43:11.282 --> 00:43:15.182
analysis, trying to see, is there some master

753
00:43:15.222 --> 00:43:18.802
transcription factor which we can potentially manipulate, which would

754
00:43:18.882 --> 00:43:22.722
overcome both the exhaustion signature and the TGF-beta signature

755
00:43:22.762 --> 00:43:25.762
concurrently? And indeed, what we saw was that

756
00:43:26.902 --> 00:43:30.522
this was 180-gene screen, again, based on the computational

757
00:43:30.562 --> 00:43:34.522
analysis. There was a single transcription factor which really stood out.

758
00:43:34.582 --> 00:43:38.542
It's a gene called Aeolus. It's IKZF3, it's

759
00:43:38.602 --> 00:43:42.242
also called. It's one of the targets of lenalidomide,

760
00:43:42.282 --> 00:43:45.802
which knocks out Ikaros and

761
00:43:45.982 --> 00:43:46.922
Aeolus.

762
00:43:47.742 --> 00:43:51.202
It hasn't really been studied very much in T cells.

763
00:43:52.642 --> 00:43:56.042
But if now we went back and looked at the mRNA in

764
00:43:56.102 --> 00:43:59.802
melanoma, you could see that Aeolus is upregulated quite

765
00:43:59.822 --> 00:44:03.602
dramatically in that setting. And when we did the

766
00:44:03.662 --> 00:44:07.402
TGF-beta knockout and we looked, what we saw is that in the knockout,

767
00:44:07.542 --> 00:44:11.242
Aeolus doesn't get upregulated, and that's consistent with the fact

768
00:44:11.302 --> 00:44:15.002
that it is a TGF-beta responsive

769
00:44:15.082 --> 00:44:18.042
gene. So TGF-beta, in part, drives Aeolus.

770
00:44:18.182 --> 00:44:19.842
It's not the only thing that drives Aeolus.

771
00:44:19.902 --> 00:44:23.802
So in the knockout, there's some expression, but it's essentially driven

772
00:44:23.822 --> 00:44:26.862
both by exhaustion and by TGF-beta.

773
00:44:27.962 --> 00:44:31.042
So based on that, we knocked out Aeolus and asked whether that would have an

774
00:44:31.082 --> 00:44:34.882
effect. And we did a mixing experiment here, where we mixed

775
00:44:35.062 --> 00:44:36.822
cells that were Aeolus knockout or not.

776
00:44:36.862 --> 00:44:40.382
And what you can see is that they lose the TGF-beta signature,

777
00:44:40.802 --> 00:44:44.282
and they have a very mitigated, if any, exhaustion signal

778
00:44:44.322 --> 00:44:47.662
compared to control T cells. They function much better,

779
00:44:48.262 --> 00:44:49.842
so that was all quite encouraging.

780
00:44:50.562 --> 00:44:52.772
But the disappointing thing was that there was a

781
00:44:53.642 --> 00:44:57.462
price to pay here, and that knocking out Aeolus resulted in less

782
00:44:57.522 --> 00:45:01.452
surviving cells. And so we were a bit surprised and

783
00:45:01.522 --> 00:45:05.282
disappointed by that. But then as we looked more into what

784
00:45:05.602 --> 00:45:09.582
cells have a motif that binds Aeolus, it turns out that many of

785
00:45:09.642 --> 00:45:13.042
the anti-apoptotic pathways are

786
00:45:13.162 --> 00:45:17.022
also affected by Aeolus. And if you knock it

787
00:45:17.122 --> 00:45:20.962
out, essentially, the cells undergo apoptosis, so they become good effector

788
00:45:21.002 --> 00:45:24.902
cells, but they don't stay alive. And so this is kind of what

789
00:45:24.922 --> 00:45:28.762
it looks like. You see the Aeolus improves therapy, but it's

790
00:45:28.802 --> 00:45:32.582
not great. So we've worked on, and I'll talk about this a little later,

791
00:45:32.782 --> 00:45:36.482
some fusion proteins that actually can provide survival

792
00:45:36.602 --> 00:45:40.542
signals, overcome this activation-induced cell death, which

793
00:45:40.602 --> 00:45:42.862
is induced through Fas, FasL, and Bb.

794
00:45:42.962 --> 00:45:46.402
And you can see in that setting, we can essentially overcome this.

795
00:45:46.462 --> 00:45:50.382
So this is telling us a bunch of things, and one of them, this was an old

796
00:45:50.422 --> 00:45:54.062
paper that we had published in "Cancer Cell" looking at what's the

797
00:45:54.162 --> 00:45:55.792
obstacles in the tumor microenvironment.

798
00:45:55.812 --> 00:45:56.862
And I think what

799
00:45:57.682 --> 00:46:01.462
you can see from the complexity is that a single modification is

800
00:46:01.472 --> 00:46:04.302
not likely to resolve the problem in solid tumors.

801
00:46:04.692 --> 00:46:08.482
And so it's going to require more, such as Aeolus and then a

802
00:46:08.522 --> 00:46:12.062
survival signal, but it's going to require more than just

803
00:46:12.082 --> 00:46:15.122
probably a single step to create cells that work.

804
00:46:16.782 --> 00:46:20.492
So we then said, well, can we change some of these immunosuppressive signals that

805
00:46:20.522 --> 00:46:24.202
these cells are receiving through inhibitory ligands and cytokines

806
00:46:24.642 --> 00:46:28.602
and change that so that the cells actually benefit from them rather

807
00:46:28.662 --> 00:46:31.842
than interfere? And this is kind of an interesting

808
00:46:32.142 --> 00:46:36.082
strategy. You can essentially become the mad scientist, the kind of things

809
00:46:36.182 --> 00:46:38.742
we all wanted to do when we started going in the lab.

810
00:46:38.782 --> 00:46:42.642
But I think the problem has become, in the current context,

811
00:46:43.142 --> 00:46:45.642
mad scientist is kind of taking on a different

812
00:46:47.062 --> 00:46:50.722
stature. It's because these days, if you're not a mad scientist, you're just not

813
00:46:50.782 --> 00:46:52.902
paying attention to what's actually going on right now.

814
00:46:53.442 --> 00:46:56.742
So with that said, I'll get back to the study.

815
00:46:56.922 --> 00:47:00.462
We've made these synthetic fusion proteins,

816
00:47:00.842 --> 00:47:04.142
which essentially, as you can see, normally have inhibitory domains.

817
00:47:04.542 --> 00:47:08.402
And what we do is we change their tails, so instead of providing inhibitory

818
00:47:08.482 --> 00:47:11.602
signals, they provide costimulatory signals.

819
00:47:11.702 --> 00:47:15.602
Or if we take something like Fas, we can change its death domain, which

820
00:47:16.702 --> 00:47:18.802
is responsible for activation-induced cell death.

821
00:47:19.162 --> 00:47:22.542
And if we put FasL on it, for example, we now get a

822
00:47:22.822 --> 00:47:25.422
pro-survival and proliferative signal.

823
00:47:25.772 --> 00:47:27.942
And essentially, you can rewire cells this way.

824
00:47:28.082 --> 00:47:28.182
You

825
00:47:29.122 --> 00:47:32.842
just use your imagination. For the number of inhibitory signals you can change

826
00:47:32.902 --> 00:47:36.462
into, rather than being bad for the T cell, the fact that the ligand's there

827
00:47:36.482 --> 00:47:40.282
becomes good. We also have done this with TGF-beta.

828
00:47:40.322 --> 00:47:44.222
Ashley Tellon in the lab did this. We took the TGF-beta receptor, which

829
00:47:44.262 --> 00:47:48.182
is a four-chain receptor. It's a little bit more complex than the IL-2 receptor.

830
00:47:48.722 --> 00:47:50.902
But we swapped the cytoplasmic tails.

831
00:47:51.242 --> 00:47:54.942
We went through a variety of constructs to make this happen, but essentially, we

832
00:47:54.982 --> 00:47:58.322
can change a cell, a receptor that binds

833
00:47:58.362 --> 00:48:02.182
TGF-beta into one that instead of suppressing the cell, delivers an IL-2

834
00:48:02.242 --> 00:48:04.742
signal, and we published that the end of last year in

835
00:48:05.722 --> 00:48:09.142
PNAS. It delivers an IL-2 signal. It attenuates the

836
00:48:09.182 --> 00:48:10.262
TGF-beta signal,

837
00:48:11.102 --> 00:48:14.222
but it doesn't fully eliminate it, which actually turns out to be important for

838
00:48:14.262 --> 00:48:17.182
maintaining a cell stemness and survival.

839
00:48:17.302 --> 00:48:19.642
So this is just showing you in an IncuCyte assay.

840
00:48:19.682 --> 00:48:23.281
This is cells in a plate where we look at how the cells,

841
00:48:24.122 --> 00:48:25.542
if they can kill them, as you can see,

842
00:48:26.862 --> 00:48:29.362
if we put the TGF-beta/IL-2 receptor, they work.

843
00:48:29.422 --> 00:48:33.282
They can kill tumors for over 150 hours, where the TCR alone

844
00:48:33.322 --> 00:48:37.082
doesn't work. And they not only kill it, but they actually proliferate.

845
00:48:37.142 --> 00:48:40.042
Again, they're getting their own IL-2 signal.

846
00:48:41.242 --> 00:48:45.062
So this functions both as a dominant negative to the native TGF-beta

847
00:48:45.082 --> 00:48:48.882
receptor, and it also takes advantage of the fact that they're going to see

848
00:48:48.962 --> 00:48:52.822
TGF-beta, so turn it into something good rather than just ignore it.

849
00:48:53.902 --> 00:48:56.742
So there's other things to do. So one is we

850
00:48:57.602 --> 00:49:01.302
actually reported back in the 1980s the critical role of CD4 cells in

851
00:49:01.342 --> 00:49:05.162
antitumor responses. It's quite clear from all the checkpoint blockade and the CAR

852
00:49:05.262 --> 00:49:08.742
cells, CAR T cell story, that CD4s are very important.

853
00:49:09.302 --> 00:49:12.262
But so far, what we were talking about was engineering CD8 cells.

854
00:49:12.662 --> 00:49:16.522
We know CD4 cells provide help. They provide indirect killing.

855
00:49:16.582 --> 00:49:20.344
They activate B cells.A little less appreciated is this

856
00:49:20.374 --> 00:49:23.464
critical role of CD4 cells with exhausted cells.

857
00:49:24.294 --> 00:49:28.234
And we're calling this CD4 assistance because the mechanism isn't really

858
00:49:28.274 --> 00:49:30.474
quite well known. But

859
00:49:31.314 --> 00:49:34.974
CD8 T cell exhaustion is in part a

860
00:49:35.014 --> 00:49:37.834
reflection of the lack of getting adequate CD4 help.

861
00:49:38.254 --> 00:49:41.734
And that's why in, for example, in the LCMV model, CD4 cells are

862
00:49:41.774 --> 00:49:45.534
depleted before you actually infect them with Clone 13.

863
00:49:46.194 --> 00:49:50.094
So we said, could we build a CD4 cell to work in this system

864
00:49:50.134 --> 00:49:52.774
without having to mix and match class

865
00:49:53.674 --> 00:49:57.414
II molecules with class I molecules and have two separate sets of

866
00:49:57.454 --> 00:50:01.283
TCRs? So we know we can put a TCR into CD8 cells, and it'll

867
00:50:01.374 --> 00:50:05.154
kill, get activated well. We say, can we put that same high

868
00:50:05.214 --> 00:50:07.994
affinity TCR into CD4 cells, and you

869
00:50:08.874 --> 00:50:11.334
get a signal with that. It isn't very good.

870
00:50:11.394 --> 00:50:15.274
But if you put in CD8 alpha beta as well as the TCR, you give the

871
00:50:15.394 --> 00:50:19.374
CD4 cell the same avidity as the CD8 cell, and that does

872
00:50:19.414 --> 00:50:23.264
work, but it works even better if we put in one of these fusion proteins that

873
00:50:23.274 --> 00:50:27.034
provides co-stimulation. CD4 cells really appreciate

874
00:50:27.074 --> 00:50:29.874
getting a costimulatory signal, and then they work much better.

875
00:50:31.034 --> 00:50:33.804
The slides here are showing you that. This is, again, HICASE assay.

876
00:50:34.124 --> 00:50:37.724
If you put in tumor alone, it grows out quite quickly, and it

877
00:50:37.774 --> 00:50:41.754
overgrows the culture. If we put in CD4 cells with just the TCR,

878
00:50:41.794 --> 00:50:45.384
they don't do anything either. But if we add CD8 alpha beta to those

879
00:50:45.394 --> 00:50:49.074
CD4 T cells, they work quite well, but again, they can't quite

880
00:50:49.114 --> 00:50:52.374
eliminate the tumor. We're adding fresh tumor every 48 hours.

881
00:50:53.294 --> 00:50:56.934
But if we put in CD8 cells, they work better, but again,

882
00:50:57.294 --> 00:51:00.764
they start losing activity over time in the absence of CD4 help.

883
00:51:01.294 --> 00:51:04.974
But if we mix fours and eights at a one-to-one ratio, so they're the same

884
00:51:05.074 --> 00:51:08.794
total number, they actually clear the tumor each time we keep adding it.

885
00:51:08.854 --> 00:51:12.434
So they maintain function, and they continue to have anti-tumor

886
00:51:12.494 --> 00:51:15.714
activity. And this got published recently.

887
00:51:16.594 --> 00:51:19.674
We're also developing now a mouse model to study this.

888
00:51:20.194 --> 00:51:23.694
I can't go through what the obstacles were doing that, but Jeanette's working on

889
00:51:23.714 --> 00:51:27.574
that. And we're also developing a multicellular human

890
00:51:27.654 --> 00:51:31.454
organoid system to actually study it in human cells in vitro.

891
00:51:33.134 --> 00:51:37.094
But I just want to show the importance of adding co-stimulation to that

892
00:51:37.154 --> 00:51:39.774
system. So this is the TCR with

893
00:51:41.034 --> 00:51:44.874
CD8 alpha beta and the TCR. This is adding the 28 signal to

894
00:51:44.914 --> 00:51:46.084
it. This is an

895
00:51:47.254 --> 00:51:51.154
irrelevant TCR, and we put this into NSG mice

896
00:51:51.194 --> 00:51:54.304
that we transplanted human melanoma into.

897
00:51:54.744 --> 00:51:58.654
And I think what you can see is the final tumor volume, and I'm not showing you

898
00:51:58.694 --> 00:52:02.354
all the data obviously, but the cells with the CD28 costim now

899
00:52:02.394 --> 00:52:05.194
work much, much better than they do without it.

900
00:52:05.234 --> 00:52:08.914
And this is just to show you graphically. I hope this is projecting well.

901
00:52:09.294 --> 00:52:11.954
The irrelevant TCR doesn't get into the melanoma.

902
00:52:12.434 --> 00:52:16.263
The TCR with CD8 alpha

903
00:52:16.314 --> 00:52:18.134
beta, the fours and eights do get in.

904
00:52:18.574 --> 00:52:22.074
But if we add co-stimulation, you can see there's far more cells in.

905
00:52:22.454 --> 00:52:23.464
And the reason that that

906
00:52:24.314 --> 00:52:27.874
piece of tissue is smaller, it's because it's actually being rejected.

907
00:52:28.194 --> 00:52:31.974
So this was nine days after infusion, and you can see already the tumor is getting

908
00:52:32.014 --> 00:52:34.234
much, much smaller than its counterparts.

909
00:52:34.594 --> 00:52:38.414
And if you blow up that area, you can see there's loads of four and eights that are

910
00:52:38.474 --> 00:52:41.354
now in the tumor, and those cells have clearly expanded.

911
00:52:41.954 --> 00:52:45.814
So based on this, we've started a trial in using a

912
00:52:45.834 --> 00:52:47.154
KRAS TCR

913
00:52:48.054 --> 00:52:51.974
in humans with, again, putting in CD8

914
00:52:52.054 --> 00:52:55.314
alpha beta and a TCR. This is A11 restricted.

915
00:52:55.344 --> 00:52:59.294
We've treated four patients now. They get treated at

916
00:52:59.354 --> 00:53:03.263
four dose levels. We're just about getting ready to start the second

917
00:53:03.734 --> 00:53:07.654
group. We also, Affinity, a company that we

918
00:53:07.674 --> 00:53:08.874
had founded,

919
00:53:09.974 --> 00:53:13.894
did a concurrent trial using the TCR, CD8 alpha beta,

920
00:53:13.954 --> 00:53:17.814
and the FES Forum BB IFP. I can't quite report that one yet, but

921
00:53:18.174 --> 00:53:19.774
I will tell you that data looks yet better.

922
00:53:20.994 --> 00:53:22.754
So these are the four patients we treated.

923
00:53:23.154 --> 00:53:27.114
I have that patient nine in gray because the patient was just

924
00:53:27.154 --> 00:53:30.374
treated, and so I have just one data point on that patient.

925
00:53:31.234 --> 00:53:35.233
This is the three patients. I don't have any longitudinal data

926
00:53:35.274 --> 00:53:36.233
on patient nine.

927
00:53:37.094 --> 00:53:40.414
But all of these patients showed evidence of anti-tumor activity.

928
00:53:41.674 --> 00:53:44.954
So this is looking at the change in the target lesion.

929
00:53:45.674 --> 00:53:48.374
You can see one patient actually didn't shrink, just had stable disease.

930
00:53:48.474 --> 00:53:50.734
Two patients had significant shrinkage.

931
00:53:51.154 --> 00:53:54.954
If you look at their tumor markers, CEA

932
00:53:55.034 --> 00:53:58.934
for colon, CEA 99 for pancreatic cancer, those

933
00:53:59.014 --> 00:54:02.634
all went down dramatically. And this last patient we just treated also

934
00:54:03.014 --> 00:54:05.714
dramatically decreased that biomarker.

935
00:54:06.334 --> 00:54:08.054
If you look at ctDNA,

936
00:54:09.054 --> 00:54:12.394
I have this on just two patients. Both of them, they completely cleared the

937
00:54:12.434 --> 00:54:16.334
ctDNA, but you can see on this one patient, came back by day 100.

938
00:54:16.394 --> 00:54:19.394
This other patient came back around day 60.

939
00:54:20.654 --> 00:54:24.314
If you take tumor biopsies from these patients, this is the

940
00:54:24.354 --> 00:54:25.914
patient showed a tumor reduction.

941
00:54:25.954 --> 00:54:28.874
You can see in the pretreatment, there was lots of tumor.

942
00:54:28.914 --> 00:54:32.554
In the post-treatment biopsy, there was very little

943
00:54:32.574 --> 00:54:35.374
tumor around. There was more T cells.

944
00:54:35.434 --> 00:54:39.294
If we looked at the CD4 cells that were in the tumor, now I'm just showing you

945
00:54:39.334 --> 00:54:42.294
there the CD4 cells that have the TCR on the left.

946
00:54:42.334 --> 00:54:46.044
And then you can see that if we stain for what genes are expressed, they're

947
00:54:46.074 --> 00:54:49.944
expressing perforin, granzyme B, Tbet, and very

948
00:54:49.974 --> 00:54:53.154
little exhaustion markers. So they're looking quite functional.

949
00:54:53.214 --> 00:54:57.074
The same thing we can say for the CD8 cells.

950
00:54:57.134 --> 00:55:00.654
They express TCF7. They don't express exhaustion

951
00:55:00.694 --> 00:55:04.154
markers. And they express markers like

